.TH $home 5
.XI $home - "Users `home' directory location"
.SH NAME
$home \- Users `home' directory location
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B $home
\fIdirectory\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B $home
contains the pathname of the users home directory. The file naming  convention
utilizes tilde ('\fC~\fR') to identify the users home directory (\fC$HOME\fR).
When entering a file name:
.CS
~/xxx    -> $home/xxx
~yyy/xxx -> $home/../yyy/xxx
.CE
On most systems this is automatically set to the environment variable "\s-1HOME\s0" if it is defined. On systems (i.e.
Microsoft Windows or MS-DOS) where there may be no home defined then the system user directory is used by default.
.PP
The value may be explicitly redefined by the user in the start-up file to be a different location. If \fB$home\fR is
re-defined then ensure that a trailing directory separator is included at the end of the pathname. 
